passages.text: We hope everyone is enjoying themselves for this last little bit of summer...as we have all seriously LABORED and worked hard this year in Auto.
From the initial Trump- euphoria through February to the lowest of the Tariff sentiment lows March/April... this year seen more Highs & Lows than a visit to Coney Island.
For the last few weeks, we have spent considerable time talking to you about "What's Next?" after a somewhat begrudging monster move upwards since April lows (and in August), our Top Picks...
Now, "What's Next?" means different things to different investors.

- The "easy \$5" has been made based on 1) Low-bar FY guides (NA production outlook once -8 to -10% in April now closing in on -3% on better SAAR and lower Tariff-related OEM price), 2) Tariff relief (parts, SK/JP to 15%, MX to come), & 3) Multi-Yr Depressed Supplier multiples at the low end of even their new secularly challenged ranges.
- The majority of Auto is now trading near 52-wk highs spare TSLA, STLA, MBLY, & LAD. TSLA/STLA deserving of it while MBLY/LAD candidates for YE reversion.
- We believe ++ MX resolution is increasingly "priced in" and may represent the last +5% for the sector through fall.
- Tariffs have made us all increasingly "short-term" traders given "macro/policy" changes minute-to-minute.

- As we approach YE, we believe investors may start to re-lengthen their Auto investment horizons to 24 months with a focus on 1) Rising SAAR (16.5-17MM goal '27), 2) Rate Cuts & Rising Credit availability. & 3) Continued ++ IHS revisions (their -4% NA '26 as almost a "gift" which could see +5-6% revisions NTM).
We believe our ++ Auto thesis (cyclical upturn within secularly challenged legacy) is increasingly CONTRARIAN. To learn more about our conviction...

- US SAAR (replacement demand/trend)  
- ALV NDR Recap (proxy for ++ production revisions)  
- BWA Thesis (latest & original U/G)  
- '27 Upside & Near-term muted RRs (inside as part of our Midweek slides)
Have a lovely weekend,

Pitstops & Macro:- ALV : Passive Safety but continued Active Execution (Rev/Mgn/Capital)- Pitstop (Wed) : Midweek - ALV NDR / STLA L3 / Hyundai Reshoring / Uber Freight / LAD Buyback / Year of AV- Pitstop (Fsri) : EU SAAR & NEVs / ++ Oscar Survey / ALV NDR Recap / ++ Production Revisions / Midweek / Year of the AV
Sept \(30^{\text{th}}\) (NYC) - 8th Annual ADAS, AV & AI Forum in NYC

Thematic:- EvrlSI Autos Q2 Preview - Cyclical Addition by Tariff Subtraction- EvrlSI Mid- Year Auto Ponderings (Conference & BWA NDR Recap)- DEALER Mid- Year Checkup: Oil Change or Start of the Race?- EvrlSI July US SAAR: 16.4MM!

Macro & Policy:- Global Policy - Federal Reserve - Cook's Lawsuit Vs Removal By Trump Raises Due Process And For Cause Standard- Global Policy - ECB Minutes Suggest EU- US Trade Deal In Line With Expectations And Outlook On Track, Pointing To Need For Weaker Data For Another Cut In 2025- Economics - Labor Market Softer In 2H- Technical Analysis - The Hole Enchiladav- Auto Dealers Survey - Auto Dealers Survey Ticks Up For A 2nd Week- Equity & Derivatives Strategy - Big Beautiful Bill Tax Benefits - Where the Cash Flow Will Go
US imports about \(- 50\%\) of 16MM SAAR (7.5- 8MM imports/yr)
\(\triangleright\) - 3.5- 4MM from JP/SK/EU \(\triangleright\) - 4MM from MX/CA
An OEM like Toyota imports about \(- 25\%\) or 600k of their 2.4MM US sales from Japan
Those 600k imports would have a \(\) 10k\(cost increase (\) \sim \\(40k\) \times 25\%\()\)
Pricing to US Consumer - all OEMs would decide 1) What to pass on and 2) What to simply not ship
Basically 3.5- 4MM MX/CA import units see \(\) 3k\(increase
4MM units (SK/JP/EU) see \(- \S 10k\) increase
\(50\%\) US produced see minor ASP increase (raw mats, components)
\*\*Work that out and its about \(\) 3- 4k\(increase or 7 - 9\%\) avg price increase if fully passed on
US USED pricing would increase dramatically and benefit Dealers/KMX, as in Covid

One interesting question (and observation) - the traditional "Auto Pie" is not likely to GROW again in the next cycle as it has in '20/21...2016 to today is still a world where 90MM+ cars are built during peak of cycle & the future profit pool of core Auto (cars produced and sold) has not likely EXPANDED (until major AV advancement)... So, who will WIN Market Cap going forward?

1. Will EV valuations rise HIGHER (Ultimate Disruption)?  
2. Or will legacy OEM Multiples revert to historical norms as they successfully transition to EVs (Evolution)?  
3. Or can both legacy & EV startups BOTH grow by NEW Markets of AV & Connectivity/SaaS?
While the total market cap of legacy OEMs has increased since '07, new entrants (notably TSLA) have GROWN the overall OEM market cap...but they haven't "stolen" it from legacy OEMs...
Source: Company Data, Evercore ISI Research
EPS is Done, Stocks Rallied POST: An early look now to Q3/2H & Possible Seasonal/'27 Turn...
Let's discuss our ALV NDR w/ CFO/IR, GM Net Tariff Math & Current Risk Rewards
Uber & AV; Dealers (AN/LAD) Top Picks, GM needs MX for \(\) 65\(; BWA/ALV suppliers. APTV/Conti/MBLY special sits
“Easy” \(\) 55\(of “better - than - feared” now over - next is either 1) Seasonal/26 upside (+20\%) or 2) Consumer /Auto stagnation
ALV gave a ++/reassuring message within framework of ++ Q3 production (upside) & US SAAR
Revenue - Q3 tracking well alongside ++ 'IHS global revisions (Q3 cons Rev looks \(1 - 2\%\) too low)
FY Rev upside potential now exists as independent forecasters are now \(+1\%\) global production '25 YoY (flatish weighted) YoY vs ALV's - 0.5% guidance assumption on Q2 report

Q3 & FY Margins - debate around "how low Q3 margin can dip below Q2's \(9.2\%\) " with under- utilization during summer shutdown given 1MM lower global units QoQ (EvrlSI est. \(9.1\%\) , Street \(9.0\%\) flat).
ALV mgmt held to the Q2 party line that Q3 mgn will be "low for the year". We see potential for low 9s on strong execution but really timing of end of Q payments

Message for FY remains "high end of mgn guide is tough" based on pass- throughs of tariffs are margin dilutive (EBIT neutral) but we see 10.3- 10.4% as likely on the 20- 30bps of extra EBIT from 100bps higher Rev
Story remains ON TRACK for strong execution and incremental mgn going fwd (11% mgn '26; 11.5- 12% '27)

Neutral as short- term Catalyst: Neither really \(+ +\) or - for the stock short- term (ie not enough of EPS momentum to get super fast \(\Phi \Phi\) involved at low/mid- single 2H/FY EPS upside. ALV could be at same \(\Phi 125\) post report....misses the point that it's a grinder of a GARPY long and likely at \(\Phi 140 - 150\) next yr on the rollover to \(\Phi 11.50 - 12\) EPS '26 & \(\Phi 14\) '27
Capital Allocation - repurchases continuing (trending \(\sim 23k\) shares/day per ALV website), largely in the stated range of \(\) 300-\(500MM/yr.\)

Valuation & Upside - ALV has had a volatile year (topping off \(\Phi 129\) last year and bottoming \(\Phi 75 - 80\) April) and currently sits at the upper/middle \(\sim 10x\) PE of its 7- 13x '26 range. Last 18 months RR of \(\Phi 70 - 130\) . We see ALV as a \(\Phi 130+\) stock exiting this year, \(\Phi 140\) by Q1'26 and possibly a \(\Phi 150+\) stock looking to '27 on cycle/margin/ownership/multiple expansion. On a 2- 3yr basis, ALV could peak at \(\Phi 170 - 180\) on 11- 12x \(\Phi 16\) EPS '28 in \(2+\) years.
Tariffs now squarely in Focus - UK (10%) JP/SK (15%) & USMCA (MX) NEXT??
Japan & South Korea Deals now announced - prior \(25\%\) vehicle tariffs cut to \(15\%\) (we previewed \(10\%\) ask). MX & USMCA are the critical ones needed NEXT!!

EvrISI Take - current Auto- country tariffs (UK \(10\%\) , JP/SK \(15\%\) ) argue MX/USMCA should receive better than the new \(15\%\) "bar". GM has said that \(\sim\) 2Bn of their \(4.5Bn\) (\\$6Bn annualized) Tariff exposure is SK.
GM Math as example - their \(\sim\) 6Bn annualized gross tariff exposure moves to \(\sim\) 5.2Bn on SK's \(40\%\) lower burden (prior \(\) 2Bn\$ from SK alone).

On Net basis, we could think about GM's \(\) 4Bn\(+ net annualized burden (or\) \ \(4+\) EPS) moving to \(\sim\) 1Bn (or under \(\) 1\(EPS) if their\) \ \(1.5Bn+\) offset program ( \(30\%\) ) stayed roughly the same absolute value (price, manufacturing changes, & cost cuts the 3 main offset buckets). Seasonal Trade (using SXAP Index as an example) - has consistently delivered a positive relative annual return every year for the past decade and a positive absolute annual return for all but 3 of the last 10 years.
SXAP is a broad- based EU Auto Index with performance characteristics similar to both the North American and Global automotive sectors.
REMINDER: the Seasonal Trade (Sept/Oct to April/May) can be \(>100\%\) of annualized Auto stock returns!!!
Oct/Nov have been some of the best historical months (Jan/Feb as well) which times well with EPS/pre- announcement resets.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
